Dear Ciesin



My name is Ole Nielsen and I work for the Australian government agency for international development (AusAID) in Jakarta on an initiative (http://www.aifdr.org) aiming to increase the capacity of the Indonesian Disaster Management Agency (http://www.bnpb.go.id) to manage the consequences of natural disasters in Indonesia. Open Source and freely available data is critical for the sustainability of this work and something we insist on for everything we produce or procure through this program. It is our hope that these products will ultimately help make people of Indonesia be safer from natural disasters through access to better information.



Part of our program is the development of an Open Source tool for rapid assessment of impact to buildings, infrastructure and population from natural disasters. It is called InaSAFE (Indonesia Scenario Assessment for Emergencies) and is described in more detail in the attached flyer.

InaSAFE is Open Source and many of the datasets it uses are freely available too (e.g. earthquake ground shaking estimates and Open Street Map building data). However, we have not been able to find a gridded population density dataset that can be bundled with the software.



That said, we are using the CIESIN population dataset glp10ag.asc to assess population being impacted by e.g. earthquake ground shaking and flood levels. However, even though this data is publicly available from http://sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu/gpw/global.jsp (thank you very much) we are aware that we cannot redistribute it without express written permission from CIESIN (e.g. indicated in http://iridl.ldeo.columbia.edu/SOURCES/.CIESIN/.GPWv2/.dataset_documentation.html).



Being able to include example baseline datasets with the software would greatly help in promoting the tool, testing the software and getting deployments off the ground quickly until more detailed local datasets are made available. For these reasons we seek CIESINâ€™s permission to distribute a gridded population dataset for Indonesia with the InaSAFE software along with the appropriate references, of course.



